docs.text: unfortunately it doesn't get much more formulaic than one tough cop .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: there's the renegade cop with the loser partner who has to many problems to explain .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the renegade has to prove his good name and is trapped between the good guys , the bad guys and some woman who really has nothing to do with the story other than being there for the purpose of providing sex for the hero in the middle of the film .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: bo dietl ( pronounced deedle , baldwin ) is one tough cop , a guy who is being investigated by hardass fbi agents due to his association with the ny mafia .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: on top of that problem , he has a drunk , gambling addicted partner ( penn ) who has a penchant for collecting parking tickets ( i guess cops aren't immune ? ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: then , throw into the mix the femme fatale ( gershon ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: right there you have plenty of ammo for a decent cop drama .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: but right in the middle of the film , they throw in a completely un-related plot point .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: dietl and his partner duke try to solve a case that they have been warned to stay away from .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the film spends over half an hour tracking the case of a nun who was beaten and raped to near death .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: once the case is solved , the film shifts focus back to the mafia issue .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: whatever neat mesh the screenwriter wanted to create between the two stories failed miserably .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: aside from being asked to accept michael mcglone as a mafioso ( an insult if you ask me ) the performances were pretty good .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: baldwin , though he occasionally slips into an impression of his brother alec , does a fine job as one tough cop .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: penn , who also slips into an impression of his brother sean , is even better as a loser tough guy cop .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: what one tough cop lacks is originality .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: this film offers nothing new .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: nothing that you can't get from any cop film .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it screams sidney lumet all over the place , perhaps because it was produced by marty and michael bregman , producers of lumet's dog day afternoon and serpico .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: but even the masterful sidney would not have been able to make one tough cop into a good film .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: too much else is lacking .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: i also saw the boom mic pop into the top of the frame twice early on in the picture , something that i almost never notice .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: but once i saw that , i had it in the back of my mind every time i saw a medium or long shot .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: at times , i was hoping to see it .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: one tough cop isn't laughable , nor is it a terrible film , but it just isn't unique .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it is a classic example of a film that didn't need to be made .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: but one thing is for sure , it could really use a better title .
docs.label: negative
